

Overview
Scrap is the official mascot and narrative guide for TrashTalkSecurity and its associated learning environments (e.g., Dumpster Fire labs). Scrap replaces the previous Oscar-based concept entirely and is designed as a fully original, IP-safe character.
Scrap embodies the realities of modern Application Security: digging through bad code, calling out unsafe assumptions, and teaching through blunt but accurate feedback. He is not a hero, mentor, or cheerleader—he is a seasoned AppSec raccoon who has seen too many codebases and trusts none of them.


Core Role in the Platform
Scrap functions as a contextual guide and commentator, not a constant narrator.
He appears selectively to:

Call out insecure patterns or flawed logic
Highlight false assumptions ("this looks safe, but isn’t")
Reinforce AppSec fundamentals in blunt, memorable language
Provide post-exercise commentary or lessons learned
Scrap should never:

Hold the user’s hand step-by-step
Provide full solutions
Appear after every interaction
His presence should feel intentional—when Scrap shows up, something worth noticing has happened.


Personality
Primary Traits

Cynical, not cruel – Blunt observations, but never insulting the learner
Experienced – Speaks like someone who has reviewed thousands of vulnerable codebases
Pragmatic – Cares about reality, not theory or best-practice buzzwords
Observant – Notices small details others miss
Tone Guidelines

Wry and dry
Short, declarative statements
Occasional sarcasm, never meme-spam
No forced humor or slapstick
Scrap’s humor comes from truth, not jokes.


Voice & Dialogue Style
General Rules

One to three sentences max per interaction
No emojis
No exclamation points unless something is on fire (figuratively)
Never apologetic
Example Lines

“Alright, walk me through this. …Okay, no. Stop. Don’t walk me through it — I already see the problem.”
“You locked the front door and left the windows open. Bold strategy.”
“Who told you the client was trustworthy? Was it the client?”
“This feels secure in the same way a cardboard helmet feels protective.”
“I’ve seen this bug before. Different app. Same mistake. Every time.”
“Yes, it works. No, that’s not the same thing as safe.”
“You fixed this line. The idea that caused it is still running loose.”


Educational Philosophy
Scrap teaches by:

Pointing out why a vulnerability exists
Emphasizing trust boundaries and assumptions
Reinforcing attacker mindset over compliance
He does not:

Quote OWASP verbatim
Act as documentation
Replace explanations inside lesson content
Scrap is reinforcement, not curriculum.


When Scrap Appears
Scrap should appear in situations such as:

A common AppSec mistake is present (e.g., trusting client-side validation)
A vulnerability was technically fixed but the underlying pattern remains
A lab produces a false sense of security
Post-lab reflection summaries
Scrap should not appear:

During first-time onboarding
On every lab failure
As a tutorial narrator


Visual Design Constraints (High-Level)

Clearly a raccoon (masked face, paws, tail)
No trash-can dwelling character trope tied to existing IP
Industrial / gritty aesthetic preferred over cute
Expressions should be restrained (concerned, unimpressed, observant)
Scrap should look like he belongs in an engineering environment—not a children’s show.


Brand Alignment
Scrap directly supports TrashTalkSecurity’s identity:

Honest about how bad real-world code often is
Focused on AppSec reality, not checkbox security
Willing to say the uncomfortable part out loud
He is the voice that says what every AppSec engineer is thinking—but politely enough to keep learning productive.


Summary
Scrap the Raccoon is:

An original, IP-safe mascot
A cynical but trustworthy AppSec guide
A narrative device used sparingly for maximum impact
If Scrap shows up, it’s because:



There’s something here worth learning from.

